passages.text: North America Equity Research 29 August 2025
See Signs U.S. Tire Industry Backdrop Growing More Favorable with Imports Finally Cresting - but Europe Likely Remains Heavily Impacted by Imports & Affordability Concern Continue

The tire industry backdrop for domestic U.S. producers was challenging during 2Q, given that the level of tire imports remained elevated for longer than was expected due to the on- again/off- again nature of tariffs, which only encouraged more pre- buying; however, according to the latest data, the influx of tire imports into the United States has finally crested and is now in the process of reversing, with imports declining as a \(\%\) of U.S. shipments to the lowest level since 2024. As per preliminary USTMA estimates, the total number of light and commercial tire shipments rose \(+0.7\%\) y/y in July, following increases of \(+0.5\%\) y/y in June, \(+0.6\%\) in May, \(+5.3\%\) in April, and \(+3.2\%\) in March. OE shipments remain softer, particularly commercial OE shipments, which sank - \(23.3\%\) y/y in July due to uncertainty surrounding the implementation of the 2027 EPA mandates. Despite the OE softness, overall shipments have been positive in recent months, with volume not the source of concern for domestic producers; rather, it has been the level of imports that have plagued domestic tire company profitability (see our August 11 report, "Goodyear: Lower Estimates as US Pre- Buy of Low- Cost Imports Lasts Longer & New Pre- Buy Arises in Europe, but Eventually Tariffs Will Flip from Headwind to Tailwind, Benefitting Earnings").

Imports have surged in recent years as price- conscious buyers (already squeezed by higher costs in unrelated consumer spending categories) sought less costly alternatives as tire manufacturers sought to pass through earlier increases in commodity and non- commodity supply chain costs and as wholesalers and retailers pre- bought lower cost imports ahead of anticipated tariffs. Imports rose from \(54.4\%\) in 2019, prior to the pandemic- era inflation spike, to an all- time high of \(70.0\%\) in April 2025, before moderating by - 390 bps m/m to \(66.3\%\) in May and now by another - 280 bps m/m in June. Low- cost imports have continued to outperform in 2025, with significant pre- buy activity extending into 2Q, but imports as a percentage of total shipments have begun to show a downward trend for two consecutive months. The pre- buy of low- cost imported tires in the U.S. lasted longer than expected, exerting greater pressure on earnings, even as tariffs are set to positively impact earnings in the second half of the year but do appear to have finally crested, and we anticipate further declines in tire imports as a percentage of total shipments going forward. That is not to say the pressure on domestic tire producer earnings will immediately abate, as affordability concerns limit the ability to take price and there remains an elevated inventory of low- cost imports in the domestic channel, but there is light at the end of the tunnel in the U.S. Looking at near- term dynamics, our channel checks indicate that consumers have continued to trade down into lower- price Tier 3 category tires, which are predominantly imported from Southeast Asian countries. However, as pre- tariff inventories deplete and non- domestic manufacturers pass through the tariff costs to consumers, we expect shifts in buying patterns that will benefit domestic manufacturers. In Europe, pressure will likely remain intense

- Tire Prices (Table 1). US tire prices, as measured by the US Bureau of Labor Statistics' Producer Price Index (PPI), were up \(+1.3\%\) m/m in July after tracking flat m/m in June. On a year-over-year basis, prices averaged \(+1.9\%\) y/y in July vs. \(+0.8\%\) y/y in June.

- US Tire Shipments (Table 3). As per preliminary USTMA estimates, the total number of light and commercial tire shipments rose \(+0.7\%\) y/y in July, after rising \(+0.3\%\) y/y in June, \(+0.3\%\) y/y in May, \(+5.6\%\) y/y in April, \(+3.2\%\) y/y in March, and falling \(-5.7\%\) y/y in February and \(-1.4\%\) y/y in January. Looking more closely at the latest \(+0.7\%\) y/y trend in July U.S. shipments, OE shipments rose \(+8.4\%\) y/y (commercial tires \(-23.3\%\) y/y and light vehicle tires \(+12.4\%\) y/y), but this was offset by overall softness in Replacement shipments, which were down \(-1.1\%\) y/y (commercial replacement tires \(+19.4\%\) y/y, light vehicle replacement tires \(-2.9\%\) y/y).

- Tire imports are showing clear signs of having earlier crested in April after accounting for -280 bps less share m/m in June and -390 bps less share m/m in May. (Table 6). Imports represented \(-63.5\%\) of total tire shipments in June, in line with \(-63.4\%\) in 2024 (which we estimate reflected pre-buy activity for much of the year), \(-60.8\%\) in 2023 (which appears to have reflected little if any discernible pre-buy activity), and \(-54.4\%\) in 2019 (prior to the inflection higher in inflation for all categories of spending).
- US Vehicle Miles Driven (Table 10). US vehicle miles traveled rose \(+1.3\%\) y/y in April after rising \(+1.5\%\) y/y in March and declining \(-0.5\%\) y/y in February.

- Raw Material Price Trends (Table 13). The weighted average cost of commodities used to manufacture a tire rose \(+0.4\%\) m/m \((-4.3\%\) y/y) in July, as per the J.P. Morgan Weighted Average Tire Commodities Index, after declining \(-0.3\%\) \(-2.1\%\) and \(-4.5\%\) m/m in June, May and April, respectively. The sequential cost increase in July was led by steel cord and natural rubber. We estimate that the trend in prices for oil derivatives, such as synthetic rubber (most recently \(-1.7\%\) m/m) and carbon black \((-0.8\%\) m/m), could continue to trend lower, apart from the impact of tariffs, on account of the \(-12\%\) YTD decline in oil prices.
